{
  "texts": [
    "The secure world, also called the trusted-execution environment (or the TEE), runs trusted software services.",
    "The normal world, or the rich-execution environment, runs untrusted applications and is normally the environment in which end-users of the device conduct the bulk of their activities.",
    "These features are implemented with traditional hardware-level protection, and a small, trusted, secure monitor that executes at a higher processor privilege level than the OS in the secure and normal worlds.",
    "The two worlds interact via a secure monitor call (smc instruction) that allows world switches.",
    "The secure world implements features such as normal world attestation (e.g., as in Knox [14])."
  ]
}